# Aorta

> The aorta is the **largest artery in the body**, arising from the left ventricle of the [[Heart]] and distributing oxygenated blood to the entire systemic circulation. It has four named segments.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- Arises from: [[Heart]] (left ventricle, aortic valve)
- First branches: [[Coronary Arteries]] (from aortic sinuses)
- Major branches: [[Carotid Arteries]], [[Subclavian Artery]], [[Celiac Trunk]], [[Renal Arteries]], [[Iliac Arteries]]
- Runs along: [[Thoracic Vertebrae]], [[Lumbar Vertebrae]]

## 🗂️ Four Segments

| Segment | Location | Key Branches |
|---------|----------|--------------|
| **Ascending aorta** | From aortic valve → aortic arch | [[Coronary Arteries]] (L & R) |
| **Aortic arch** | Superior mediastinum | Brachiocephalic trunk → [[Carotid Arteries]] + [[Subclavian Artery]] (right); Left [[Carotid Arteries]]; Left [[Subclavian Artery]] |
| **Descending thoracic aorta** | T4 → T12 (diaphragm) | Intercostal arteries (T3–T11), bronchial arteries |
| **Abdominal aorta** | T12 → L4 (bifurcation) | [[Celiac Trunk]] (T12), SMA (L1), [[Renal Arteries]] (L1–L2), IMA (L3), [[Iliac Arteries]] (L4) |

## 🔑 Aortic Arch Branches (Left to Right — Memorize)
1. **Brachiocephalic trunk** (innominate) → right common carotid + right subclavian
2. **Left common carotid**
3. **Left subclavian**

## 🔑 Abdominal Aorta Branches (Unpaired visceral)
- **Celiac trunk** (T12) — [[Celiac Trunk]]: stomach, spleen, liver
- **Superior mesenteric artery** (SMA, L1) — small bowel + proximal colon
- **Inferior mesenteric artery** (IMA, L3) — distal colon + rectum

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Aortic aneurysm** — abnormal dilatation >3 cm (AAA) or >4.5 cm (thoracic)
  - AAA: most common in infrarenal aorta; pulsatile abdominal mass; rupture → catastrophic hemorrhage
  - Risk: male, elderly, smoking, hypertension, family history
  - Screening: abdominal USS in men >65 who have ever smoked
- **Aortic dissection** — intimal tear → blood enters media → two lumens
  - Type A (ascending) — surgical emergency; risk of coronary/aortic valve/brain involvement
  - Type B (descending only) — medical management (anti-impulse therapy)
  - Classic: sudden "tearing" chest/back pain; unequal arm blood pressures
- **Coarctation of the aorta** — congenital narrowing, usually at ligamentum arteriosum (just distal to left subclavian)
  - Upper body hypertension, lower body hypotension; rib notching on CXR
  - Associated with Turner syndrome, bicuspid aortic valve
- **Aortitis** — inflammation; causes: Takayasu's arteritis, giant cell arteritis, syphilis


